<p class="cl-l">Theresa Bridget Malone had been born in Farnworth near Bolton, but at the 1901 census (then age 15), was living with her
    widowed mother Christina at 92 Sussex Street, Lower Broughton, working as a blouse finisher. This was just across the river
    from East Robert Street where John Edward's dad had died in 1906 - you could cross on Blackfriars Road or Springfield Lane.</p>
	
<p>So John Edward and Theresa almost certainly lived in the same vicinity for some time and quite possibly went to the same
    church (St Peter's on Greengate?). Here is an extract from a picture of John Edward. If you look at the whole photo, you
    will see two other people and a motor car. The identity of the baby is officially unknown (although see below), but the
    woman is Molly Kavanagh, the eldest of the Malone siblings, more formally called Annie. Of course if you used her nickname,
    her maiden name would have been Molly Malone! But instead of a wheelbarrow, there is a car, and if dad is to believed
    in Down the Arches, almost the only car around in those days was that owned by Kate and Richard Noonan. As it looks like
    a Singer Tourer rather than the infamous Iron Lung which came later, that would date the photo to pre-1934. The Singer had
    been acquired in the mid to late 1920s.</p>

<p>John and Molly's dress suggests a funeral, although they are not visibly sad at the moment
    the photo is taken (by whom?). Could this be September 1927 (RIP Christina Malone) or October 1932 (RIP Richard [I] Noonan)? If
    the former, Richard [II] might have been driving the car and taking the photos, and the baby might be our Aunt Cath, who had
    been born about four months earlier. This seems doubly plausible as it was Cath who supplied us with the photo.
</p>

<p>The only record that we have been able to find of Theresa's marriage - other than the civil register listing - is the miracle
    "prediction" attached to John's 1889 catholic baptism record. So although we know the date was 17 September 1910 and the church
    was St Boniface's in Lower Broughton, we currently have no further details such as witnesses or addresses. It is interesting that
    the marriage was celebrated at St Boniface's, as it must then have been in its earliest days of being a church in the sense
    we generally understand that word (maybe that's why we can't find the church marriage record).</p>

<p>Like the Mother of God and St James' in Pendleton some decades earlier, St Boniface's had started as a catholic mission into the city,
    with a single priest operating from his front room. But it eventually became one of the main Catholic venues for Lower Broughton.</p>

