<p>Here is a picture of Theresa Bridget Noonan (nee Malone). We don't know when, where or by whom it
    was taken, but as she was born around 1886, the picture might be from the 1940s. She died aged 70 in 1956, but John Edward
    survived to 1987 and died at the grand old age of 98.</p>

<p>St Boniface's was on the eastern bank of the river almost due north of John Edward's place and almost due west of Mary Ann's place,
    very close to Gerald Road. If you crossed the river westwards on Gerald Road, this would lead directly back to Charlestown
    and Whit Lane. On the way, you would pass the turn into Littleton Road on your right, and that is where John Edward and
    Theresa would settle for decades just a year or two after the 1911 census.</p>

<h6>The Malone Quarter</h6>
<p>Richard's occupation in 1911 (whilst sharing with John and Theresa) was as an Assistant Salesman at a Plumbers'
    Merchants. John's was as a Tramway Conductor with the "Corporation", although I don't know whether this would be Salford
    or Manchester. It is a reasonable guess that he got the job through a family connection, as Theresa's two next eldest sisters,
    Agnes and Margaret, were both married to Tramway Conductors. In fact, it turns out that John Edward had not just married his
    sweetheart Theresa, he had been co-opted into a very tightly-knit local clan which had colonised its own corner of 
	Lower Broughton.</p>
		 	 
<p>Four older and two younger siblings of Theresa's appear in Salford at the 1911 census. The younger ones, Winnie and Joseph,
    were still living with Christina. The older brother and three older sisters were all married and had set up their own
    households very close to Christina's, and John Edward and Theresa were no exception. Every address was within a few minutes'
    walk of every other. It was almost its own <i><b>Malone Quarter</b></i> within Lower Broughton, headed by a (presumably) 
	benevolent matriarch.</p>

